SQL (Structured Query Language) acts as a Data Manipulation Language (DML) when it is used to manipulate data stored in a database. DML includes commands that allow you to retrieve, insert, update, and delete data within the tables of a relational database.


🔧 Common DML Commands in SQL


SELECT – Retrieves data from one or more tables.


SELECT name, age FROM students WHERE age > 18;

INSERT – Adds new rows of data to a table.


INSERT INTO students (name, age) VALUES ('Alice', 20);

UPDATE – Modifies existing data in a table.


UPDATE students SET age = 21 WHERE name = 'Alice';

DELETE – Removes rows from a table.


DELETE FROM students WHERE name = 'Alice';



✅ Key Characteristics of DML in SQL


Targets Data, Not Structure: DML commands work within the structure defined by DDL (Data Definition Language). They don’t change tables or schemas.

Transactional: DML operations can be rolled back or committed, making them part of SQL's transactional control.


BEGIN;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;

Conditional Execution: WHERE clauses are used to specify which rows are affected.



💡 Example Use Case


Suppose you have a table employees(id, name, salary):


Increase the salary of employees who earn less than 50000:


UPDATE employees SET salary = salary + 5000 WHERE salary < 50000;

Add a new employee:


INSERT INTO employees (id, name, salary) VALUES (101, 'John Doe', 55000);



